<Layout title="Exploring Pluto" description="Telescopes, missed flybys, and the long-distance study of Pluto.">
  <h1>Exploring Pluto From Afar</h1>
  <p>
    No spacecraft has ever landed on Pluto, and only one has ever visited it.
    Almost everything we knew about Pluto for most of its history came from
    patient observation across billions of kilometres of space.
  </p>

  <h2>The telescope era</h2>
  <p>
    For decades Pluto was studied only as a faint point of light. The Hubble
    Space Telescope produced the first crude surface maps in the 1990s and
    2000s, resolving Pluto into little more than a few blurry light and dark
    patches. Ground-based telescopes measured its atmosphere by watching how
    Pluto dimmed the light of distant stars as it passed in front of them.
  </p>

  <!-- Content image deliberately missing alt (image-alt) -->
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/pluto-true-color.jpg" width="320" class="content-img" />
    <figcaption>The kind of detail only achievable up close — impossible from Earth.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>The flyby that almost was</h2>
  <p>
    NASA's Voyager 1, launched in 1977, could in principle have been routed past
    Pluto. Mission planners instead chose a close flyby of Saturn's giant moon
    Titan, which sent Voyager 1 out of the plane of the planets and made a Pluto
    encounter impossible. Pluto would have to wait nearly 40 more years for a
    visitor.
  </p>

  <h2>Watch: a tour of the Pluto system</h2>
  <!-- Embedded video iframe with NO title attribute (frame-title) -->
